snippet.textDisplay:
Just want to say, I'm type 1 diabetic from the UK, England. I started doing the gym on & off a year ago, but since last October, started being consistent 3x a week. I even took up the services of a couple of sessions with a personal trainer at the gym & it just made me more inclined to give up than keep going. But I started to watch your video's & I have to say thank you. I quickly spotted some of the mistakes I was making, made adjustments & still felt I wasn't being confined to a routine of someone else's making by my own. It kept my gym workouts enjoyable & I felt good every time I finished.

Although I didn't take up your workout program myself, I have recommended it to others who are in more dire need of help who have taken up your program themselves.

So again, fantastic video's & keep up the amazing work you do.

P.s. Is there any alternative to the inclined dumbbell press I could do on a machine, say on the Functional Trainer or something? It's just I've found that I can press weights I can barely get into position to do the workout.

Thanks in advance :)

snippet.textDisplay:
Jeff. I am only a couple weeks younger than you and have trained on and off (more on than off) since I was 13. I have learned so much since subscribing to your channel nearly 2 years ago. From my mid 30s to early 40s, I lost all of my gains from my high school college years from stupid/careless training and poor nutrition. I've had a multitude of injuries over the years the worst of which was herniating my l4/l5 in sept 18. After clearing 3 months of PT at the end of 2018. I went back to the gym, and thanks to the post-therapy workout plan my PT gave me and largely to your workout videos I have regained a lot of my pre-injury strength and put on 15 lbs of muscle I lost and I haven't had any more injuries and minimal aches and pains. I am actually lifting somewhat heavy again. At least my upper body. I can't do full back squats with much weight, but I can leg press 545 lbs for a few reps (much prefer the Bulgarian split squats though). Your videos are not only informative but have taught me to be more analytical about my training and consistent and diligent with eating clean. I am born again thanks to your videos.

My one request...please write a Athlean X Training encyclopedia or several books comparable to Arnold's. I'm old school.
